The article discusses the Twentieth Anniversary of the Violence Against Women Act (VAWA), which was signed into law in 1994. The VAWA changed the way the United States responds to domestic abuse and sexual assault, providing vital services for victims and improving the criminal justice system. The article emphasizes the importance of strengthening the protections provided by the VAWA and reaffirms the basic human right to be free from violence and abuse. It also highlights the progress made in reducing domestic violence but acknowledges that more work needs to be done. The article concludes with a proclamation from President Barack Obama, calling on men and women of all ages, communities, organizations, and levels of government to work together to end violence against women.